
[1]mimical

   MIM'ICAL, a. [L. mimus, mimicus; Gr. to imitate.]

   1. Imitative; inclined to imitate or to ape; having the practice or
   habit of imitating.

   Man is of all creatures the most mimical in gestures, speech, &c.

   2. Consisting of imitation; as mimic gestures.

   Mimic implies often something droll or ludicrous, or less dignified
   than imitative.
